        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>St. Thomas</placeName>
                <date>18<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Sept/62</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Your esteemed letter came<lb/> to hand in due course, and their
                several in<lb/>closures were delivered. The Books were like<lb/>wise received, and I
                have disposed of a few<lb/> of them. I felt sorry to learn by your last<lb/> of your
                indisposition, and trust that your<lb/> health has since been quite restored. I
                am<lb/> interested in the article on Education in the<lb/> Occident. Here things
                fluctuate much, I<lb/> regret to say. The succeeding numbers of the<lb/> Occident
                for <persName>Mr. Myers</persName> you will please for<lb/>ward to
                    <placeName>Jamaica</placeName>. <persName>Mr. David</persName> having left<lb/>
                that <placeName>Island</placeName> some time since for <placeName>Sydney</placeName>.<lb/>
                <persName>Mr. M.</persName> was offered the situation of Minister<lb/> of the German
                congregation there, a much</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>better one than he enjoyed here, and he therefore<lb/> left our shores on
                    <date>Tuesday</date> night.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">It does indeed appear as if nothing but the<lb/> war is now thought
                of in <placeName>America</placeName>: still I<lb/> think it is natural, and the
                world looks on<lb/> anxiously at the contest now waging. Here<lb/> there is nothing
                of interest to dilate upon; and<lb/> without even the change of seasons to mark<lb/>
                the progress of time, each year seems to pass<lb/> away unperceived, but for the
                trials which<lb/> beset every life. The New Year and ensuing<lb/> holy days are
                again fast approaching, and<lb/> I therefore conclude this with friendly
                greet<lb/>ings thereon. That our Heavenly Father may<lb/> inscribe you to a happy
                life is the earnest<lb/> hope of,</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">Rev. Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(12)">
                <persName role="author">D. M. Pizal</persName>
            </p>
